Federal Government is set to issue a second Green Bond of up to N15 billion, the Debt Management Office (DMO) has announced. According to the DMO, the issuance is following the successful debut Green Bond Issuance of N10.69 billion in December 2017, of which the DMO stated that Nigeria became the first African country to issue a Green Bond. Through the Offer, the federal government seeks to raise N15 billion to finance projects with green credentials. These eligible green projects can be classified under three (3) themes within the green bond framework, namely: renewable energy, afforestation, and transportation. “To ensure the success of the Series II Green Bond (“the Offer”), the Federal Ministry of Finance, Federal Ministry of Environment and the Debt Management Office (“DMO”) will be engaging investors at respective Roadshows in Lagos and Abuja on May 27, 2019 and May 28, 2019,” the statement said. It also said the “Series II Green Bond issuance is a further demonstration of the FGN’s commitment to the reduction of greenhouse gas emissions by 20% (unconditionally) by 2030, as outlined under the Paris Agreement signed on September 21, 2016”. DMO also noted that Moody’s Investors Service has assigned a GB1 (Excellent) Green Bond Assessment to the Offer. It also said it is working with Chapel Hill Denham Advisory Limited, Capital Assets Limited, Rand Merchant Bank Nigeria Limited, and Stanbic IBTC Capital Limited as Financial Advisers/Issuing Houses to the Offer.  DMO begins roadshow for N10.9bn green bond in Lagos, Abuja FG offers N10.7bn Green Bonds at 13.48% - DMO DMO begins roadshow for N10.96bn green bond Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin